Project Direction Exploration for a Quantum Cryptography System
Team X

	Recent research in quantum cryptography explores methods for performing computation on encrypted quantum data while preserving the confidentiality of the original information. One notable direction is quantum homomorphic encryption (QHE), which allows a server to evaluate quantum circuits on encrypted quantum states without learning the underlying data. The work by Dulek, Schaffner, and Speelman demonstrates that compact quantum homomorphic encryption for polynomial-size circuits is possible when combining quantum techniques with classical leveled homomorphic encryption schemes. This work also highlights the connection between QHE and blind delegated quantum computation, where a client can outsource quantum computations to a more powerful server while keeping the inputs and algorithm private.
	While the theoretical framework is well developed in the literature, implementing a full research-grade construction is beyond the scope of a typical semester project. Instead, the goal of this project is to identify a feasible applied-cryptography direction that captures the core ideas of quantum cryptography while still allowing the team to build a functional prototype. To determine the most appropriate path, three candidate project directions were considered.
	The first candidate project focuses on implementing a simplified simulation of quantum homomorphic encryption. In this design, a client encrypts a quantum state using a quantum one-time pad and submits it to a server capable of performing restricted circuit evaluation. The server then evaluates a set of allowed quantum gates on the encrypted data and returns the resulting encrypted state to the client for decryption.
	The motivation for this direction comes directly from the literature on quantum homomorphic encryption. Clifford gates can be applied relatively easily to quantum states protected by the quantum one-time pad, while non-Clifford gates such as the T gate require additional mechanisms. The referenced research proposes techniques for supporting these gates using auxiliary classical cryptographic primitives.
	Although this candidate would closely follow the research work, it introduces substantial implementation complexity. Even a restricted version would require building a quantum circuit simulator, implementing encryption transformations on qubit states, and handling special gate cases. As a result, much of the project effort could shift toward approximating the research algorithm itself rather than building a well-engineered cryptographic system with clearly defined interfaces and lifecycle management.
	For these reasons, while this candidate offers strong academic relevance, it may be difficult to complete within the constraints of a small team and limited development time.
	The second candidate focuses on the protocol layer of blind delegated quantum computation rather than attempting to implement the full cryptographic construction described in the literature. In this design, a client packages a quantum computation request and submits it to a server that performs the computation on behalf of the client. The protocol is designed to protect the confidentiality of the client’s inputs and computation parameters while allowing the server to execute the requested quantum circuit.
	Under this model, the project emphasizes secure message formats, authenticated communication, session key management, and strict validation of protocol messages. The system would include clearly defined API endpoints for job submission, evaluation, and result retrieval. Each request would contain structured metadata such as job identifiers, circuit descriptors, and cryptographic authentication fields.
	The actual quantum computation component would be implemented using a restricted simulator capable of handling a limited class of circuits. For example, the first version of the system could support Clifford-only circuits, which are easier to simulate and align with theoretical discussions of encrypted quantum computation. More advanced features, such as limited support for T gates, could be added in later iterations.
	This approach shifts the primary focus of the project toward applied cryptographic engineering rather than purely theoretical implementation. It allows the team to develop a system that includes a threat model, misuse prevention strategies, and a defined key lifecycle while still remaining grounded in the research motivation of secure delegated quantum computation.
	The third candidate examines the problem from a systems security perspective. Instead of implementing quantum cryptographic primitives directly, the project would focus on designing a secure key lifecycle and policy framework for workflows involving quantum cryptographic operations.
	In this system, the emphasis would be on how cryptographic keys are generated, distributed, rotated, and revoked when managing encrypted quantum computations. The project would simulate a quantum computation service where clients submit encrypted jobs, but the primary research contribution would lie in designing the key management infrastructure required to support such a service securely.
	This direction would involve building mechanisms for session key derivation, secure storage of key contexts, and automated revocation in the event of suspected compromise. Logging and audit capabilities would also be included to track cryptographic operations and detect abnormal activity.
	While this candidate offers strong relevance to applied cryptography, it may feel somewhat disconnected from the core topic of quantum cryptography. The system would focus primarily on classical infrastructure rather than directly demonstrating the principles of secure quantum computation described in the literature.
	After evaluating the three options, the team selected Candidate Project 2: Blind Delegated Quantum Job Protocol as the primary project direction.
	This approach provides the best balance between theoretical grounding and practical feasibility. It directly incorporates the idea of delegated quantum computation described in the literature while avoiding the complexity of implementing a full quantum homomorphic encryption scheme. Instead of reproducing the entire research construction, the project focuses on building a secure protocol that supports the workflow of delegated quantum computation.
	The selected design allows the team to implement several critical elements expected in a real cryptographic system. These include clearly defined message formats, authenticated communication channels, session key management, and explicit error handling. The project will also include a threat model describing potential adversaries and misuse scenarios, along with safeguards to prevent replay attacks, malformed requests, and key misuse.
	Another advantage of this direction is that it allows the project to remain extensible. The initial implementation can support a limited class of circuits while leaving room for more advanced cryptographic features in future work. For example, later versions of the system could integrate more sophisticated encryption mechanisms or support a broader set of quantum gates.
	Overall, this direction provides a practical way to explore quantum cryptography from a systems perspective while remaining grounded in current research. It demonstrates how theoretical advances in secure quantum computation could translate into real-world cryptographic infrastructure, making it an appropriate and achievable focus for the project.
